default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Police and Crime Commissioner has over £400m per year to spend on making people in West Yorkshire safer and feeling safer.  The majority of this is delegated to West Yorkshire Police and under the control of the Chief Constable, with the remainder spent on community safety projects that help prevent crime, support victims and achieve
default the other priorities within
default the Police and Crime Plan.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Panel’s role is to scrutinise and support the Police and Crime Commissioner’s decisions about the use of resources in West Yorkshire.  Over the last 12 months, we have:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default5.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt’s good news that crime in West Yorkshire is falling and the Panel recognises the vital role played by those who work in our local communities to make them safer.  The Panel feels it would be helpful for residents to have clearer milestones and contextual information to allow them to reach their own judgements about the Police and Crime Commissioner’s 
defaultprogress.
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe PCC holds fortnightly Community Outcome meetings with the Chief Constable, which is the principal route by which he is held to account.  The Panel understands its role to be to ask the PCC to explain how he has ensured that the Chief Constable is ensuring the outcomes in the Police and Crime Plan are achieved.  This includes priorities the PCC has identified alongside the Chief Constable to focus on; the evidence that has been used to identify those priorities and what tangible improvements the PCC and Chief Constable expect to see. 
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Panel also seeks to understand how the PCC and Chief Constable respond to financial information about the Force’s Programme of Change and its overarching budgetary position. 
defaultAgain, the Panel looks to triangulate information from meetings with evidence from the OPCC or external partners like HMIC.  
default&#xa0;
default6.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs Forces across Yorkshire and the Humber move to a new model of regional collaboration through a ‘lead force’ model rather than a collective resource, the Panel will look for evidence that the PCC is holding the Chief Constable to account for those areas where West Yorkshire leads, and to make sure that local residents are being well-served on issues that are led by colleagues elsewhere. 
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
